Capstone Project Leadership Experience:
During our capstone project, I served as the assistant leader. My role wasn’t just about holding a title — I carried a lot of responsibility to make sure the team stayed on track and understood the product we were building.

I was the one researching what materials and tools we needed to buy, making sure our choices were practical and within budget. I also discussed the structure of the product with the team, breaking down the process step by step so everyone could understand how it worked. This helped us stay aligned and avoid confusion.

On top of that, I sometimes took the lead in announcing and organizing our meet‑ups. Keeping everyone informed and connected was part of making sure the project moved forward smoothly. I also communicated directly with our Research and Capstone teacher whenever necessary, ensuring that our team stayed guided and aligned with expectations.

Managing the initial product and handling the tech side alone taught me initiative and accountability. But guiding the team through explanations, updates, and teacher communication showed me the importance of leadership and clear communication. I learned that being a leader isn’t just about doing the work — it’s about helping others understand, staying motivated, and moving together toward the goal.
